| {{flag|Switzerland}} 
| [[Davos]]
| {{sort|2018-01-25|25 January}}
| May addressed and met with business leaders at the [[World Economic Forum]] in Davos.
|-
| {{flag|China}} 
| [[Wuhan]], [[Beijing]] and [[Shanghai]]
| {{sort|2018-01-31|31 January – 2 February}}
| May pursued deals in China.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/31/world/asia/theresa-may-china.html</ref>
|-
| {{flag|Germany}}
|[[Berlin]] and [[Munich]]
| {{sort|2018-02-16|16–17 February}} 
| May held a meeting with German Chancellor Angela Merkel in Berlin and attended the annual Munich security conference.<ref>https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-43071696</ref><ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/17/world/europe/uk-theresa-may-munich.html</ref>
|-
|{{flag|Belgium}}
|[[Brussels]]
|{{sort|2018-03-22|22 – 23 March}}
|May attended the European Union Summit. There she was preoccupied with responding to the [[Poisoning of Sergei and Yulia Skripal|Skripal poisoning]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-43498310|title=May's Russia mission faces Brexit test|last=Kuenssberg|first=Laura|date=2018-03-22|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-04-09|language=en-GB}}</ref>
|-
|{{flag|Denmark}}
|[[Copenhagen]]
|{{sort|2018-04-09|9 April}}
|May met the Prime Minister of Denmark Lars Løkke Rasmussen to discuss the Skripal poisoning, security cooperation, Britain's exit from the EU and bilateral trade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/apr/08/theresa-may-scandinavia-row-russia-salisbury-attack-skripal-nerve-agent|title=May makes Scandinavia trip amid row with Russia over Salisbury attack|last=Crerar|first=Pippa|date=2018-04-08|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-04-09}}</ref> 
|-
|{{flag|Sweden}}
|[[Stockholm]]
|{{sort|2018-04-09|9 April}}
|May met the Prime Minister of Sweden Stefan Löfven to discuss the Skripal poisoning, security cooperation, Britain's exit from the EU and bilateral trade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/apr/08/theresa-may-scandinavia-row-russia-salisbury-attack-skripal-nerve-agent|title=May makes Scandinavia trip amid row with Russia over Salisbury attack|last=Crerar|first=Pippa|date=2018-04-08|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-04-09}}</ref>
|-
|{{flag|Bulgaria}}
|[[Sofia]]
|{{sort|2018-05-17|17 May}}
|May met EU leaders in the Western-Balkans summit to discuss security, and the Irish Taoiseach Leo Varadkar to discuss the Irish border.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-44152103|title=Theresa May security pledge at EU summit|last=Crerar|first=Pippa|date=2018-05-17|website=BBC News|language=en|access-date=2018-05-17}}</ref>
|-
|{{flag|Macedonia}}
|[[Skopje]]
|{{sort|2018-05-17|17–18 May}}
|May became the first British Prime Minister to visit Macedonia in 20 years. She discussed post-Brexit trade with Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/960888/brexit-news-Theresa-May-UK-commitment-EU-security-West-Balkans-summit-Macedonia/amp|title=Theresa May to announce BOLD vision for UK commitment to EU security post-Brexit|last=Crerar|first=Pippa|date=2018-05-17|website= Daily Express|language=en|access-date=2018-05-17}}</ref>
|-
| {{flag|Canada}}
| [[La Malbaie]]
| {{sort|2018-06-07|7–9 June}}
| May attended the [[44th G7 summit|G7 summit meeting]] in [[La Malbaie]].
|-
| {{flag|Belgium}}
| [[Brussels]]
| {{sort|2018-06-28|28–29 June}}
| May attended the European Union Summit.
|-
| {{flag|Netherlands}}
| [[The Hague]]
| {{sort|2018-07-03|3 July}}
| May met with Dutch Prime Minister [[Mark Rutte]] for continuing discussions on Britain's Departure from the European Union with a good deal.
|-
